(TCF)-binding element of the cyclin D1 promoter and activates its transcription. 
Interestingly, telomerase is also recruited to the cyclin D1 promoter in a 
TERC-dependent manner through the interaction with NOL1, further enhancing 
transcription of the cyclin D1 gene. Depletion of NOL1 suppresses cyclin D1 
promoter activity, thereby leading to induction of growth arrest and altered 
cell cycle distributions. Collectively, our findings suggest that NOL1 
represents a new route by which telomerase activates transcription of cyclin D1 
gene, thus maintaining cell proliferation capacity.

