BACKGROUND: Skeletal-related events (SREs; pathologic fracture, radiation or 
surgery to bone, spinal cord compression) frequently occur in patients with 
advanced cancer with bone metastases/lesions. Limited data on the associated 
patient and economic burden are available to aid in resource planning and 
evaluating treatment options.
METHODS: Patients with bone metastases/lesions secondary to breast, lung or 
prostate cancer or multiple myeloma; with at least one SRE within 97 days prior 
to enrollment; life expectancy of at least 6 months; and Eastern Cooperative 
Oncology Group performance status 0, 1 or 2 were recruited. Information on 
health resource utilization (HRU; including number/duration of hospitalizations, 
outpatient visits, procedures), attributed by investigators to be associated 
with a SRE, was collected retrospectively for up to 97 days prior to enrollment 
